1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,480
Hello, everyone, and welcome back to another lesson here at EnglishPod.
大家好，欢迎回到EnglishPod的另一节课。

2
00:00:07,480 --> 00:00:08,480
My name is Marco.
我是Marco。

3
00:00:08,480 --> 00:00:09,480
And my name is Katrin.
我是Katrin。

4
00:00:09,480 --> 00:00:11,520
So, Marco, what are we talking about today?
那么，Marco，我们今天要聊什么？

5
00:00:11,520 --> 00:00:18,600
Today, we are taking a look at a guy who is a little bit too afraid of people in general.
今天，我们要看一个对别人有点过于害怕的家伙。

6
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:22,600
There's a good word for this in English, someone who's almost too afraid all the time, someone
英语里有个好词来形容这种人，一个几乎总是过度害怕的人，一个

7
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:24,760
who is overly cautious.
过于谨慎的人。

8
00:00:24,760 --> 00:00:26,240
We call this person paranoid.
我们称这种人为偏执狂。

9
00:00:26,240 --> 00:00:33,520
Okay, so if you are paranoid, you think that everyone wants to hurt you or that everyone
好吧，如果你偏执，你会觉得每个人都想伤害你，或者每个人都

10
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:34,520
is out to get you.
在算计你。

11
00:00:34,520 --> 00:00:35,520
Wait, did you hear that?
等等，你听到了吗？

12
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:36,520
No, I didn't.
不，我没听到。

13
00:00:36,520 --> 00:00:37,520
Did you hear that?
你听到了吗？

14
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:38,520
Someone at the door.
有人在门口。

15
00:00:38,520 --> 00:00:39,520
Marco, can you check that?
Marco，你能去看看吗？

16
00:00:39,520 --> 00:00:40,520
Okay, that's paranoid.
好吧，这就是偏执。

17
00:00:40,520 --> 00:00:45,240
You know, you're always hearing voices and noises and things.
你知道，你总是听到声音和动静什么的。

18
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:48,000
Yeah, so a paranoid, somebody that is paranoid.
是啊，所以偏执狂，就是那种偏执的人。

19
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:52,560
All right, so why don't we listen to this dialogue for the first time and see what this
好了，那我们第一次听这段对话，看看这个

20
00:00:52,560 --> 00:00:54,240
person is all paranoid about.
人在为什么事情偏执。

21
00:00:54,240 --> 00:00:55,240
There he is again.
他又来了。

22
00:00:55,240 --> 00:01:09,280
Dan, Dan, dude, you have to come over to my house right now.
Dan，Dan，老兄，你现在就得来我家。

23
00:01:09,280 --> 00:01:11,000
Is everything okay?
一切都还好吗？

24
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:20,080
Just get over here.
赶紧过来。

25
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:23,360
Come in, quickly.
快进来。

26
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:26,720
So since when is your house a bank?
所以你家什么时候变成银行了？

27
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:27,720
What do you mean?
你什么意思？

28
00:01:27,720 --> 00:01:32,480
I mean, what's up with the four locks and iron bars on your windows?
我是说，你窗户上那四把锁和铁栏杆是怎么回事？

29
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:34,360
Security Dan, security.
安全措施，Dan，安全措施。

30
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:36,360
You can never be too safe, you know.
你知道，再怎么小心都不为过。

31
00:01:36,360 --> 00:01:39,040
A lot of sickos out there.
外面有很多变态。

32
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:44,680
Just the other day, they caught that peeping Tom red handed, had a high power telescope
就在前几天，他们当场抓住了那个偷窥狂，他窗户边放着高倍望远镜

33
00:01:44,680 --> 00:01:47,520
and binoculars by his window.
和双筒望远镜。

34
00:01:47,520 --> 00:01:49,200
What's the matter with you?
你怎么了？

35
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:50,200
Why are you acting all paranoid?
你为什么表现得这么偏执？

36
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,200
Paranoid?
偏执？

37
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:52,200
I'm not paranoid.
我不偏执。

38
00:01:52,200 --> 00:01:53,520
I'm cautious.
我是谨慎。

39
00:01:53,520 --> 00:01:59,360
You see, Dan, we have to be on guard at all times.
你看，Dan，我们必须时刻保持警惕。

40
00:01:59,360 --> 00:02:02,880
People just invade your privacy as if they knew you.
人们就像认识你一样侵犯你的隐私。

41
00:02:02,880 --> 00:02:09,440
Telemarketers, solicitors, even your bank, they have way too much information.
电话推销员、上门推销员，甚至你的银行，他们掌握的信息太多了。

42
00:02:09,440 --> 00:02:13,200
I like to keep everything on a need to know basis.
我喜欢一切按需知原则来。

43
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:17,120
Okay, well, what did you want to see me about?
好吧，那你找我有什么事？

44
00:02:17,120 --> 00:02:18,520
You're being watched.
你被监视了。

45
00:02:18,520 --> 00:02:19,520
Be careful, Dan.
小心点，Dan。

46
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:20,520
Be careful.
小心点。

47
00:02:20,520 --> 00:02:27,400
All right, we're back.
好了，我们回来了。

48
00:02:27,400 --> 00:02:34,480
So, yeah, I think this guy is a little bit too cautious.
所以，是啊，我觉得这家伙有点过于谨慎了。

49
00:02:34,480 --> 00:02:38,200
I would have to agree with you and I would go so far as to call him paranoid.
我同意你的看法，我甚至会说他是偏执狂。

50
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:42,720
But there's a lot of great stuff in this dialogue that we can use in a lot of different situations.
但这段对话里有很多好东西，我们可以在很多不同场合使用。

51
00:02:42,720 --> 00:02:48,440
So let's take a look at some of these new words in today's language takeaway.
那我们来看看今天“语言要点”中的一些新词。

52
00:02:48,440 --> 00:02:50,640
Language takeaway.
语言要点。

53
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:54,200
All right, the first word on language takeaway today is sicko.
好的，今天“语言要点”的第一个词是sicko。

54
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:58,480
Sicko is also the name of a movie that was a documentary famous in America by Michael
Sicko也是一部电影的名字，是迈克尔·摩尔在美国拍的一部著名纪录片。

55
00:02:58,480 --> 00:02:59,480
Moore actually.
实际上。

56
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:05,560
But a sicko in this context means someone who is a bit weird in a bad way.
但在这个语境下，sicko指的是一个有点坏心眼、古怪的人。

57
00:03:05,560 --> 00:03:09,160
So if you tell somebody you're sick, but like in that tone, right, you're saying you're
所以如果你对某人说你病了，但用那种语气，对吧，你是在说

58
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:10,920
sick, you're a sick person.
你病了，你是个有病的人。

59
00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:11,920
You're gross.
你真恶心。

60
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:12,920
Right.
对。

61
00:03:12,920 --> 00:03:13,920
You're saying you're gross.
你是在说你真恶心。

62
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:18,760
So people who have inappropriate humor, who make jokes about not so nice things.
所以那些有不恰当幽默感、拿不太好的事情开玩笑的人。

63
00:03:18,760 --> 00:03:19,760
Right.
对。

64
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:20,760
Yeah, they're sick.
是啊，他们有病。

65
00:03:20,760 --> 00:03:25,560
But in this case, sickos are people who maybe like to hurt other people, people who are
但在这个例子里，sickos指的是可能喜欢伤害别人的人，有点

66
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:29,760
a little bit crazy, people who are not normal.
疯狂的人，不正常的人。

67
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:32,840
So it's not a nice way of calling someone crazy, right?
所以这不是一个说某人疯了的友善方式，对吧？

68
00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:35,080
If you say, oh, he's a sicko, it's not really nice.
如果你说，哦，他是个变态，这不太友好。

69
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:36,080
Not at all.
一点也不。

70
00:03:36,080 --> 00:03:39,520
It's a way of saying that you're almost scared of this person because they're kind of weird
这是一种表达你几乎害怕这个人的方式，因为他们有点古怪

71
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:41,600
and almost they have problems.
而且几乎有问题。

72
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:42,600
All right.
好的。

73
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:43,920
So that's a sicko.
所以这就是sicko。

74
00:03:43,920 --> 00:03:45,800
Moving on to our next word.
接着看下一个词。

75
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:48,400
We saw that the guy was afraid of telemarketers.
我们看到那个人害怕电话推销员。

76
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:49,400
Exactly.
没错。

77
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:50,400
So what are these guys?
那这些人是什么？

78
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:53,720
Well, we've got two words being put together here, tele and market.
嗯，这里有两个词组合在一起，tele和market。

79
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:58,760
So tele, like telephone, telephone, over communication.
所以tele，像电话，通过通信。

80
00:03:58,760 --> 00:03:59,760
So they're not in person.
所以他们不是面对面。

81
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:02,080
They're people who call you up and market things.
他们是打电话给你推销东西的人。

82
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:04,460
They try to sell you stuff over the phone.
他们试图通过电话卖东西给你。

83
00:04:04,460 --> 00:04:06,520
So this is very common.
这很常见。

84
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:10,220
You get a phone call on your cell phone and they ask you if you're happy with your long
你手机接到电话，他们问你对你现在的长途

85
00:04:10,220 --> 00:04:14,980
distance calling plan or if you need new TV cable or something like that.
通话计划是否满意，或者你是否需要新的电视电缆之类的。

86
00:04:14,980 --> 00:04:19,840
And they always call during dinner or late at night, which drives me nuts.
而且他们总是在晚餐时间或深夜打电话，这让我抓狂。

87
00:04:19,840 --> 00:04:21,080
So these are telemarketers.
所以这些就是telemarketers。

88
00:04:21,080 --> 00:04:24,140
These are people who call you trying to sell things to you.
这些是打电话给你试图卖东西的人。

89
00:04:24,140 --> 00:04:27,320
And very similar to these is a solicitor.
和这些很相似的是solicitor。

90
00:04:27,320 --> 00:04:28,320
Exactly.
没错。

91
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:32,760
But the big difference here with solicitors and telemarketers is that solicitors actually
但solicitor和telemarketer的主要区别在于，solicitor实际上

92
00:04:32,760 --> 00:04:33,960
go to your house.
会去你家。

93
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:35,560
They knock on your door.
他们敲你的门。

94
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:39,120
So they're also called door to door salesmen or saleswomen.
所以他们也被称为上门推销员。

95
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:40,120
That's right.
没错。

96
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:41,120
Door to door salesmen.
上门推销员。

97
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:43,080
They go from door to door trying to sell things.
他们挨家挨户地试图卖东西。

98
00:04:43,080 --> 00:04:47,480
But in this case, a solicitor is someone who comes to your house to try to get you to do
但在这个例子里，solicitor是来你家试图让你做

99
00:04:47,480 --> 00:04:48,480
something, to buy something.
某事、买东西的人。

100
00:04:48,480 --> 00:04:49,480
All right.
好的。

101
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:50,480
Very good.
很好。

102
00:04:50,480 --> 00:04:54,440
And moving on to our next word, we have a peeping Tom.
接着看下一个词，我们有peeping Tom。

103
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:55,440
That's right.
没错。

104
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:56,440
We heard this a little bit earlier in the dialogue.
我们之前在对话里听到过这个词。

105
00:04:56,440 --> 00:05:01,480
And a peeping Tom is again a negative thing to say about someone.
而peeping Tom又是一个说某人的负面词汇。

106
00:05:01,480 --> 00:05:05,960
A peeping Tom, well, the word peep means to look, but kind of like, yeah, it's a quick
Peeping Tom，嗯，peep这个词意思是看，但有点像，是啊，是快速

107
00:05:05,960 --> 00:05:06,960
look.
看一眼。

108
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:10,600
A peeping Tom is a person who spies on other people.
Peeping Tom是指偷窥别人的人。

109
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:11,600
Okay.
好的。

110
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:15,080
So a synonym of a peeping Tom would be a voyeur.
所以peeping Tom的同义词是voyeur。

111
00:05:15,080 --> 00:05:16,080
A voyeur.
偷窥者。

112
00:05:16,080 --> 00:05:21,360
So someone who, without getting caught, tries to look at other people while they're in their
所以是指那些不被发现、试图看别人在家里的

113
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:22,360
homes.
情况的人。

114
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:26,200
And so it's really bad because it's usually inappropriate.
这真的很糟糕，因为这通常是不恰当的。

115
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:29,840
It's usually people who are watching women get undressed or...
通常是那些看女人脱衣服或……的人。

116
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:30,840
Right.
对。

117
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:35,240
So a peeping Tom is just an informal way of saying a voyeur or somebody who is spying on
所以peeping Tom是voyeur或偷窥别人的非正式说法。

118
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:36,240
people.
对。

119
00:05:36,240 --> 00:05:38,800
So those are the words for today in Language Takeaway.
这些就是今天“语言要点”中的词。

120
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:43,240
Let's listen to our dialogue again and then we'll be right back.
我们再听一遍对话，然后马上回来。

121
00:05:43,240 --> 00:05:54,600
Dan, Dan, dude, you have to come over to my house right now.
丹，丹，老兄，你现在就得来我家。

122
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:56,320
Is everything okay?
一切都还好吗？

123
00:05:56,320 --> 00:05:59,060
Just get over here.
赶紧过来。

124
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:02,320
Come in, quickly.
快进来。

125
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:05,720
So since when is your house a bank?
所以你家什么时候变成银行了？

126
00:06:05,720 --> 00:06:06,720
What do you mean?
你什么意思？

127
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:11,000
I mean, what's up with the four locks and iron bars on your windows?
我是说，你窗户上那四把锁和铁栏杆是怎么回事？

128
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:12,480
Security, Dan!
安全措施，丹！

129
00:06:12,480 --> 00:06:13,480
Security!
安全！

130
00:06:13,480 --> 00:06:15,200
You can never be too safe, you know.
再怎么小心都不为过，你知道的。

131
00:06:15,200 --> 00:06:18,040
A lot of sickos out there.
外面变态多得很。

132
00:06:18,040 --> 00:06:21,320
Just the other day, they caught that peeping Tom red-handed.
就在前几天，他们当场抓住了那个偷窥狂。

133
00:06:21,320 --> 00:06:26,520
Had a high-power telescope and binoculars by his window.
他窗户边放着高倍望远镜和双筒望远镜。

134
00:06:26,520 --> 00:06:28,200
What's the matter with you?
你怎么了？

135
00:06:28,200 --> 00:06:29,200
Why are you acting all paranoid?
你为什么表现得这么疑神疑鬼的？

136
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:30,200
Paranoid?
疑神疑鬼？

137
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:31,200
I'm not paranoid!
我才没有疑神疑鬼！

138
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:32,200
I'm cautious!
我是谨慎！

139
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:38,280
You see, Dan, we have to be on guard at all times.
你看，丹，我们必须时刻保持警惕。

140
00:06:38,280 --> 00:06:41,800
People just invade your privacy as if they knew you.
人们就像认识你一样侵犯你的隐私。

141
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:45,240
Telemarketers, solicitors, even your bank.
电话推销员、上门推销员，甚至你的银行。

142
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:48,280
They have way too much information.
他们掌握的信息太多了。

143
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:52,160
I like to keep everything on a need-to-know basis.
我喜欢凡事按需告知。

144
00:06:52,160 --> 00:06:53,160
Okay.
好吧。

145
00:06:53,160 --> 00:06:56,040
Well, what did you want to see me about?
嗯，那你找我有什么事？

146
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:57,440
You're being watched!
你被监视了！

147
00:06:57,440 --> 00:06:59,120
Be careful, Dan.
小心点，丹。

148
00:06:59,120 --> 00:07:00,120
Be careful.
小心点。

149
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:06,960
Now we're back and we had some interesting phrases in the dialogue.
现在我们回来了，对话中有一些有趣的短语。

150
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:11,240
The first one being, you can never be too safe.
第一个是“再怎么小心都不为过”。

151
00:07:11,240 --> 00:07:12,480
Fluency Builder.
流利度训练。

152
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:15,600
Alright, so this is a common mom phrase.
好了，这是一个常见的妈妈式说法。

153
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:19,200
You often hear mothers say this when they're sending their kids off to school or whatever.
你经常听到妈妈们在送孩子上学之类的时候说这个。

154
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:22,680
They say, don't talk to strangers and the kid says, well, why not?
她们会说，别跟陌生人说话，然后孩子问，为什么不行？

155
00:07:22,680 --> 00:07:24,840
You can never be too safe.
再怎么小心都不为过。

156
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:27,280
It's good to err on the side of caution.
宁可谨慎过头也好。

157
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:33,480
So it's okay to be extra, extra safe or extra cautious, just in case.
所以多一分安全或多一分谨慎是没问题的，以防万一。

158
00:07:33,480 --> 00:07:34,480
Exactly.
没错。

159
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:38,680
You never know what's going to happen, so it's better to be cautious than not.
你永远不知道会发生什么，所以谨慎总比不谨慎好。

160
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:40,720
And that's what this person is saying.
这就是这个人想说的。

161
00:07:40,720 --> 00:07:42,880
He's saying, well, security, it's important.
他在说，嗯，安全很重要。

162
00:07:42,880 --> 00:07:44,320
You can never be too safe.
再怎么小心都不为过。

163
00:07:44,320 --> 00:07:46,560
You never know what might happen.
你永远不知道会发生什么。

164
00:07:46,560 --> 00:07:48,240
Is there another way that we can combine it?
有没有另一种说法可以搭配使用？

165
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:50,120
Like you can never be too careful?
比如“再怎么小心都不为过”？

166
00:07:50,120 --> 00:07:51,120
Exactly.
没错。

167
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:52,480
Basically, the same thing.
基本上是一样的意思。

168
00:07:52,480 --> 00:07:53,480
Same thing.
一样的意思。

169
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:54,480
Yeah.
是的。

170
00:07:54,480 --> 00:07:55,480
Alright.
好的。

171
00:07:55,480 --> 00:07:56,480
What's our next phrase?
下一个短语是什么？

172
00:07:56,480 --> 00:08:00,040
We're going to talk about this peeping Tom, this person that they caught.
我们要谈谈这个偷窥狂，他们抓住的那个人。

173
00:08:00,040 --> 00:08:02,120
They caught him red-handed.
他们当场抓住了他。

174
00:08:02,120 --> 00:08:03,760
We caught you red-handed.
我们当场抓住了你。

175
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:05,920
Or he's been caught red-handed.
或者他被当场抓住了。

176
00:08:05,920 --> 00:08:06,920
So what does that mean?
那是什么意思？

177
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:13,320
It's a very colorful phrase and I don't just mean that because we're calling him red-handed,
这是一个很生动的短语，我这么说不仅仅是因为我们叫他“红手”，

178
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:18,800
but to catch red-handed means to catch someone while they're doing something wrong.
而是“当场抓住”的意思是在某人做坏事时抓住他。

179
00:08:18,800 --> 00:08:24,720
So if I see you breaking into someone's house and I say, Marco, stop.
所以如果我看到你闯入别人家，我说，马可，住手。

180
00:08:24,720 --> 00:08:25,720
I'm catching you.
我抓住你了。

181
00:08:25,720 --> 00:08:26,720
Stop now.
马上停下。

182
00:08:26,720 --> 00:08:27,720
I just caught you red-handed.
我刚刚当场抓住了你。

183
00:08:27,720 --> 00:08:29,720
You saw me doing the act.
你看到我在做那件事。

184
00:08:29,720 --> 00:08:30,720
Exactly.
没错。

185
00:08:30,720 --> 00:08:34,720
And another way of saying this is you caught him with his hand in the cookie jar.
另一种说法是“你抓到他手伸进饼干罐里了”。

186
00:08:34,720 --> 00:08:35,720
Okay.
好的。

187
00:08:35,720 --> 00:08:37,720
And this is another great phrase.
这也是一个很棒的短语。

188
00:08:37,720 --> 00:08:42,760
You can imagine a child who sees the cookies in a very special jar on the counter in the
你可以想象一个孩子看到厨房台子上一个特别的罐子里的饼干，

189
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:45,400
kitchen and mom says, don't eat the cookies.
妈妈说，别吃饼干。

190
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:49,320
Well, the child goes into the kitchen and sees the cookies and opens the jar and puts
然后孩子走进厨房，看到饼干，打开罐子，

191
00:08:49,320 --> 00:08:52,560
his hand in the jar and then mom comes and says, caught you.
把手伸进去，这时妈妈过来说，抓住你了。

192
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:55,120
That's a boy with his hand or a child with their hand in the cookie jar.
那就是一个手伸进饼干罐里的孩子。

193
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:56,120
So it's the same thing.
所以是一样的意思。

194
00:08:56,120 --> 00:08:59,280
I can say, I caught you with your hand in the cookie jar.
我可以说，我抓到你手伸进饼干罐里了。

195
00:08:59,280 --> 00:09:00,280
Or you were caught red-handed.
或者你被当场抓住了。

196
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:01,880
All right.
好的。

197
00:09:01,880 --> 00:09:06,360
And our last phrase for today is you are on a need to know basis.
今天最后一个短语是“你按需告知”。

198
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:07,360
All right.
好的。

199
00:09:07,360 --> 00:09:08,360
This is a great one.
这个很棒。

200
00:09:08,360 --> 00:09:11,120
This is often said in spy movies, I think.
我觉得这经常在间谍电影里出现。

201
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:13,520
So we say you're on a need to know basis.
所以我们说“你按需告知”。

202
00:09:13,520 --> 00:09:17,640
That means that if you really need to know something, then I will tell you.
意思是如果你真的需要知道某件事，那我就会告诉你。

203
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:19,160
But if not, I won't.
但如果不需要，我就不说。

204
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:22,420
So you only have the information that is necessary.
所以你只拥有必要的信息。

205
00:09:22,420 --> 00:09:24,280
No more or less.
不多不少。

206
00:09:24,280 --> 00:09:25,280
You're on a need to know basis.
你按需告知。

207
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:26,280
Right.
对。

208
00:09:26,280 --> 00:09:27,920
So I say, tell me, Marco, tell me what happened.
所以我说，告诉我，马可，告诉我发生了什么。

209
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:28,920
I want to know.
我想知道。

210
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:29,920
Right.
对。

211
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:33,480
And I can say, no, no, you're on a need to know basis and you don't need to know this.
然后我可以说，不，不，你按需告知，你不需要知道这个。

212
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:35,000
All right.
好的。

213
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:40,540
So a need to know basis, as you say, very popular among spy movies and government movies
所以按需告知，就像你说的，在间谍电影和政府电影里很常见，

214
00:09:40,540 --> 00:09:41,540
and stuff like that.
还有类似的东西。

215
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:42,540
Conspiracy movies.
阴谋论电影。

216
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:43,540
Yeah.
是的。

217
00:09:43,540 --> 00:09:44,540
All right.
好的。

218
00:09:44,540 --> 00:09:50,280
So let's listen to this dialogue for the very last time and we'll be right back.
那么让我们最后再听一遍这段对话，我们马上回来。

219
00:09:50,280 --> 00:10:02,040
Dan, Dan, dude, you have to come over to my house right now.
丹，丹，老兄，你现在就得来我家。

220
00:10:02,040 --> 00:10:03,760
Is everything okay?
一切都还好吗？

221
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:12,840
Just get over here.
赶紧过来。

222
00:10:12,840 --> 00:10:16,080
Come in quickly.
快进来。

223
00:10:16,080 --> 00:10:19,480
So since when is your house a bank?
所以你家什么时候变成银行了？

224
00:10:19,480 --> 00:10:20,480
What do you mean?
你什么意思？

225
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:25,240
I mean, what's up with the four locks and iron bars on your windows?
我是说，你窗户上那四把锁和铁栏杆是怎么回事？

226
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:27,120
Security, Dan security.
安全措施，丹，安全。

227
00:10:27,120 --> 00:10:28,680
You can never be too safe.
再怎么小心都不为过。

228
00:10:28,680 --> 00:10:31,800
You know, a lot of sickos out there.
你知道，外面变态多得很。

229
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:37,480
Just the other day, they caught that heaping Tom red handed, had a high power telescope
就在前几天，他们当场抓住了那个偷窥狂，他窗户边放着高倍望远镜

230
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:40,280
and binoculars by his window.
和双筒望远镜。

231
00:10:40,280 --> 00:10:41,960
What's the matter with you?
你怎么了？

232
00:10:41,960 --> 00:10:42,960
Why are you acting all paranoid?
你为什么表现得这么疑神疑鬼的？

233
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:43,960
Paranoid?
疑神疑鬼？

234
00:10:43,960 --> 00:10:44,960
I'm not paranoid.
我才没有疑神疑鬼。

235
00:10:44,960 --> 00:10:45,960
I'm cautious.
我是谨慎。

236
00:10:45,960 --> 00:10:52,080
You see, Dan, we have to be on guard at all times.
你看，丹，我们必须时刻保持警惕。

237
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:55,600
People just invade your privacy as if they knew you.
人们就像认识你一样侵犯你的隐私。

238
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:59,040
Telemarketers, solicitors, even your bank.
电话推销员、上门推销员，甚至你的银行。

239
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:02,160
They have way too much information.
他们掌握的信息太多了。

240
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:05,920
I like to keep everything on a need to know basis.
我喜欢凡事按需告知。

241
00:11:05,920 --> 00:11:06,920
Okay.
好的。

242
00:11:06,920 --> 00:11:09,880
Well, what did you want to see me about?
嗯，你想见我有什么事？

243
00:11:09,880 --> 00:11:11,240
You're being watched.
你被监视了。

244
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:12,240
Be careful, Dan.
小心点，丹。

245
00:11:12,240 --> 00:11:13,240
Be careful.
小心点。

246
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:24,320
All right.
好吧。

247
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:26,280
So the guy's a little bit paranoid.
所以这家伙有点偏执。

248
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:27,920
There's another word for this as well.
还有一个词也可以形容这个。

249
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:28,920
Similar, right?
类似，对吧？

250
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:29,920
It's schizo.
是“精神分裂”。

251
00:11:29,920 --> 00:11:35,160
Schizophrenia is a disease and a lot of people have it and it's not too uncommon, but a popular
精神分裂症是一种疾病，很多人都有，并不罕见，但一个流行的

252
00:11:35,160 --> 00:11:37,920
slang word to say someone's crazy is schizo.
俚语说某人疯了就是“精神分裂”。

253
00:11:37,920 --> 00:11:43,000
So if you guys remember this movie, A Beautiful Mind, it's all about this famous mathematician.
所以如果你们记得这部电影《美丽心灵》，它讲的是这位著名的数学家。

254
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:45,280
He's named John Nash.
他叫约翰·纳什。

255
00:11:45,280 --> 00:11:46,480
And well, he was a genius.
嗯，他是个天才。

256
00:11:46,480 --> 00:11:52,380
He came up with game theory and a lot of subsequent usage of this for economy, for many things.
他提出了博弈论，后来被广泛应用于经济学和许多领域。

257
00:11:52,380 --> 00:11:55,160
But it was proven that he was a schizophrenic, right?
但事实证明他患有精神分裂症，对吧？

258
00:11:55,160 --> 00:11:56,520
A paranoid schizophrenic.
一种偏执型精神分裂症。

259
00:11:56,520 --> 00:12:03,320
So not only did he kind of have experienced reality in different ways, but he's also paranoid.
所以他不仅以不同方式体验现实，而且还偏执。

260
00:12:03,320 --> 00:12:06,680
So he was afraid that the government was trying to kill him.
所以他害怕政府要杀他。

261
00:12:06,680 --> 00:12:12,520
And so he was, he was irrationally afraid of everything going on around him.
所以他对他周围发生的一切都毫无理性地害怕。

262
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:17,480
And it made him very unsafe because he could hurt himself or hurt other people.
这让他非常不安全，因为他可能伤害自己或伤害别人。

263
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:22,200
And the interesting thing about this is that there is no actual cure for it.
有趣的是，这实际上没有治愈方法。

264
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:24,960
You just learn to cope and live with it.
你只能学会应对并与之共存。

265
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:27,000
So you never really get cured.
所以你永远不会真正痊愈。

266
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:28,400
You just kind of live with it.
你只是学着与之共存。

267
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:30,560
Learn how to understand what's real and what's not.
学会理解什么是真实的，什么不是。

268
00:12:30,560 --> 00:12:32,160
So it's interesting.
所以这很有趣。

269
00:12:32,160 --> 00:12:36,080
It's a great movie also, by the way, if you've never seen it or you get a chance to watch
顺便说一句，这也是一部很棒的电影，如果你没看过或有机会看

270
00:12:36,080 --> 00:12:37,080
it.
的话。

271
